The glomerular capillary membrane makes the filtration barrier that allows for the passage of certain substances from the blood into the glomerular filtrate. This membrane consists of three major layers: capillary endothelium, capillary basement membrane, and layer of epithelial cells surrounding the outer surface of the capillary basement membrane (podocytes). The capillary endothelium layer is freely permeable to everything in the blood except for red blood cells and platelets, up to a size of 4 nm in diameter. The capillary basement membrane contains proteins, such as laminin, type VI collagen, nidogen, and heparan sulfate proteoglycan (HSPG). These proteins form a meshwork which effectively prevents filtration of plasma proteins. The layer of podocytes surround the capillary basement membrane and have long foot-like processes with gaps in-between called slit pores, which are 25 nm wide. It is through these slit pores that the glomerular filtrate moves. The total area of glomerular capillary endothelium across which filtration occurs in humans is approximately 0.8m. This membrane is selective in how it permits materials through, allowing related to their size, charge, and other properties.<br />
